docs.lead_paragraph: Students at the University of Southern California got a crash course in investigative journalism this summer by reporting on a powerful, scandal-ridden institution: their own school.

headline.main: A School for Scandal Is a Haven for Student Journalists
headline.print_headline: At U.S.C., Investigative Journalism Gets Close to Home for Students

docs.abstract: Arnstadt’s embrace of a giant new battery plant for electric cars illustrates Europe’s ambivalence toward Chinese investment: Jobs trump geopolitics.
docs.snippet: Arnstadt’s embrace of a giant new battery plant for electric cars illustrates Europe’s ambivalence toward Chinese investment: Jobs trump geopolitics.
docs.lead_paragraph: ARNSTADT, Germany — Officials in Brussels or Berlin may fret about China’s growing sway over the European economy, about the ports under its control and the high-tech firms that Chinese firms have acquired. But that is not a concern one hears in Arnstadt, a Baroque-era German hamlet where, long ago, Johann Sebastian Bach was the church organist.

headline.main: With a $2 Billion Factory From China, a German City Lets Others Worry
headline.print_headline: China Invests in Germany, to No One’s Dismay

docs.abstract: The economy seems to be cooling off. Whether it starts to shrink is the question.

docs.lead_paragraph: The United States is on recession watch as market signals flash red. Manufacturing is straining under President Trump’s trade war, business investment is slowing and consumer confidence is showing cracks.

headline.main: Recession or Slowdown? Why You Should Care About the Difference
headline.print_headline: A Cooling Economy, Sure. A Recession? Complicated.

docs.abstract: The fashion brand filed for an I.P.O. last week, a move signifying how much better positioned it is than its parent company for the current retail environment.

docs.lead_paragraph: When J. Crew started opening Madewell stores in 2006, the company declared that its new brand would deliver “real, honest women’s clothes” for hip 20- and 30-somethings. “Not too trendy, not too girly, just cool clothes infused with a modern upbeat attitude,” it said in a release at the time, promoting the worn-in feel of the retailer’s T-shirts, jeans and chinos.

headline.main: Madewell Diverges From J. Crew as a Darling of Casual America
headline.print_headline: A Star Casually Upstaging J. Crew

docs.abstract: The University of Chicago has long been associated with the idea that antitrust decisions should be based on prices for consumers, not market dominance. That’s starting to change.
docs.snippet: The University of Chicago has long been associated with the idea that antitrust decisions should be based on prices for consumers, not market dominance. That’s starting to change.
docs.lead_paragraph: Convocation speeches are usually filled with inspiring life lessons or sage advice, but this year’s graduating class at the University of Chicago heard something else: a battle cry against tech monopolies from one of the school’s leading economists.

headline.main: A Challenge to Big Tech and Antitrust Thinking in a Surprising Place

docs.abstract: The central bank appears poised to cut interest rates for the first time since the financial crisis. Here’s what to keep an eye on.
docs.snippet: The central bank appears poised to cut interest rates for the first time since the financial crisis. Here’s what to keep an eye on.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Federal Reserve is almost universally expected to cut interest rates when its meeting wraps up on Wednesday, the first reduction since officials slashed them to near zero in 2008, during the dark days of the financial crisis.

headline.main: A Preview of the Fed Meeting
